      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "Project South's financial model is characterized by its role as a movement-building hub. In 2023, it managed <cite id=\"8\">total assets of $19,397,907</cite>, which allows it to provide substantial support to smaller grassroots organizations. Its grantmaking strategy is robust, with top recipients including <cite id=\"9\">GS4GND receiving $4,750,376</cite> and the <cite id=\"10\">Gulf Coast Center for Law receiving $1,000,311</cite>. This model of 're-granting' ensures that funds reach frontline community organizers who may lack the administrative infrastructure to manage large-scale federal or foundation grants directly."
      ],
      "summary": "Project South is a social justice organization rooted in the Southern Freedom Movement, dedicated to eliminating poverty and genocide through community-led advocacy and movement building. Based in Atlanta, the organization focuses on developing leadership and strategic planning within marginalized communities to address systemic inequality. In the 2023 fiscal year, the organization reported <cite id=\"1\">total revenue of $11,980,885</cite>, primarily driven by <cite id=\"2\">$11,634,794 in public contributions</cite>. Project South operates as a significant grantmaker, distributing <cite id=\"3\">$11,415,862 in domestic grants</cite> to 26 different recipients to bolster local movement-building efforts. The organization maintains a <cite id=\"4\">program expense ratio of 86.7%</cite>, ensuring that a substantial majority of its resources are directed toward its core mission of social justice and advocacy. Financially, the charity demonstrates high efficiency in its development efforts, spending only <cite id=\"5\">$0.02 to raise every $1</cite> in revenue. While the organization experienced a <cite id=\"6\">3-year revenue CAGR of -35.1%</cite> following a period of high growth, it remains financially resilient with <cite id=\"7\">30.9 months of working capital</cite> available to sustain its long-term advocacy goals.",
